The Rehabilitation Engineering and Assistive Technology Society of North America (RESNA) held its annual conference as part of RehabWeek, a conference collaboration by six member-societies in Toronto, Ontario, Canada from June 24-28, 2019.  Approximately 2,000 individuals attended the conference representing multiple disciplines to discuss and learn about research, policy and practice regarding assistive technology provision and services for people with disabilities. The Annual Student Design Challenge (SDC) final decisions and awards were presented at this conference.

RESNA designed the SDC to promote and foster innovative and creative design of assistive technology hardware and/or software used by or in support of individuals with disabilities.  The SDC has been supported by the National Science Foundation (NSF) for more than a decade. This support has been critical to the continuation and expansion of the SDC.  n addition to inspiring students to work on design projects which will enhance the independence of individuals with disabilities, it is also designed to encourage, support and mentor students in various disciplines to become aware of and involved in the assistive technology (AT) and rehabilitation engineering fields.

We received 39 submissions for the 2019 SDC. A team of scholars and assistive technology practitioners reviewed each submission to ensure adherence to the structured outline of the submission requirements.  Evaluation criteria included:



Design adequately addresses problem posed by the student/client team;
Prototype uses sound engineering or design approaches, which promote safety and use by targeted client/population;
Creativity is evident in the proposed solution, and it represents a new addition to the field of assistive technology;
Students have evaluated and/or validated the prototype in an iterative way with their targeted client/population;
Students are capable of communicating their ideas well, within structured guidelines, without errors or omissions;
Prototype is functional, as viewed in their product video.


Six teams were named as finalists, and members of these teams attended the conference and professionally presented an oral defense of their design.  The finalists also presented their work at the RESNA Developers? Showcase, an interactive forum where conference participants provided informal interaction with each student team.

The generous support of NSF funded travel and accommodations for 12 students representing 6 teams to attend the RehabWeek.  A one year RESNA membership was provided by RESNA to all finalists.  Presentation and judging of the finalist teams took place within the conference, in a 2-hour session open to all conference attendees.  All teams were recognized at the final RehabWeek plenary and presented Certificates for their SDC participation at the Developers? howcase, another event held during the conference.  RESNA received sponsorship and in-kind support from RESNA?s Joey Wallace Scholarship Fund, the IMPACT Center at the University of Pittsburgh, the Center for Translation and Advancement of Rehabilitation Engineering Advances and Technology (TREAT), and the RERC on AAC.

The Student Design Challenge is designed to build on efforts of RESNA to inspire students to work on design projects that will enhance the independence of individuals with disabilities. Exposure to the professional assistive technology community at the RESNA Annual Conference provides many students with their entry into the field, and student finalists have frequently moved on to become leaders in assistive technology.

The winner of the 2019 Student Design Challenge was ATOM, the "Adaptive Tongue-Operated Mouse," submitted by Michael Laffin, Kyle Cleven, Dexter Rausch of the University of Wisconsin-Stout. The device allows people to use a tongue-operated mouse to use computers and computer applications. 





